  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ryes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Tice  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Tice","meanings":["English: variant of   Teece  ,   Tye  , or <b>Tyas</b>. The latter is an ethnic name from Anglo-Norman French <i>t(i)eis</i>, <i>tiais</i> ‘Teuton, German’, denoting someone from Germany or the Low Countries, or occasionally a habitational name from Thiais in Val-de-Marne, France.","Americanized form of German   Theiss   or possibly   Theus  .","Americanized form of Dutch and Flemish   Thys   or of its variants <b>Thijs</b> (Dutch and Flemish) and <b>Tijs</b> (Dutch)."]}]},{"name":"Olive","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a medieval given name, <i>Oliff(e)</i>, derived via French from the Late Latin name <i>Oliva</i>, which was borne by two obscure early saints. It in turn is derived from the Latin name for the olive tree, and was no doubt adopted at first because of the associations of the olive tree with peaceful productivity and fruitfulness; the olive branch has been a symbol of peace since biblical times. Like many names denoting plants and flowers, it was particularly popular in the early decades of the 20th century.  See also  Olivia ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Olive de Ryes was born about 1063, in Europe, her father, Hubert I Adam Fitz de Ryes, was 26 and her mother, Agnès de Tosny, was 21. She had at least 1 son with Raoul I de la Haye."},"et":{"about 1063–":"umbes 1063–Surnud","1063–Female":"1063–Surnud","1066–1095":"1066–1095","1085–1154":"1085–1154","1038–1107":"1038–1107","1043–1130":"